    <app id="App1">
      <sec id="Sec29">
        <title>Appendix</title>
        <sec id="Sec30">
          <title>Appendix A: method description</title>
          <p id="Par60">This section contains a full description of the base method implemented in estimateR. This method was developed by Huisman et al. and the text of Appendix A is adapted from the original method publication [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR18">18</xref>], with modifications specific to estimateR (main modifications are listed in the “<italic>Handling issues relating to incomplete data</italic>” section of the main text).</p>
          <sec id="Sec31">
            <title>Smoothing of noisy observations</title>
            <p id="Par61">To smooth the incidence data, estimateR implements local polynomial regression (LOESS). By default, estimateR performs LOESS smoothing with 1st order polynomials and a smoothing parameter <inline-formula id="IEq124"><alternatives><tex-math id="M225">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\sigma$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M226"><mml:mi>σ</mml:mi></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq124.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> set such that 21 time steps in the local neighbourhood of each point are included.</p>
            <p id="Par62">Importantly, <inline-formula id="IEq125"><alternatives><tex-math id="M227">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\sigma$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M228"><mml:mi>σ</mml:mi></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq125.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> should be adapted by estimateR users to the level of noise observed in their raw incidence data. This can be done by smoothing the raw observations with varying <inline-formula id="IEq126"><alternatives><tex-math id="M229">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\sigma$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M230"><mml:mi>σ</mml:mi></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq126.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> values until the smoothed trend matches expectations.</p>
            <p id="Par63">Before smoothing, the raw time series of observations <inline-formula id="IEq127"><alternatives><tex-math id="M231">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$(O_0, \dots , O_N)$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M232"><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>O</mml:mi><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mo>⋯</mml:mo><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>O</mml:mi><mml:mi>N</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq127.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> is padded at its left boundary with values extrapolating the initially observed trend (see the “<italic>Handling issues relating to incomplete data</italic>” section of the main text). To extrapolate these values, we first compute the average ratio between the incidence observed on a time step and the previous time step:<disp-formula id="Equ1"><label>1</label><alternatives><tex-math id="M233">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} a&amp;= \frac{1}{n} \sum _{i = 0}^{n-1} \frac{O_{i+1}}{O_i}, \end{aligned}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M234" display="block"><mml:mrow><mml:mtable><mml:mtr><mml:mtd columnalign="right"><mml:mi>a</mml:mi></mml:mtd><mml:mtd columnalign="left"><mml:mrow><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mfrac><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mi>n</mml:mi></mml:mfrac><mml:munderover><mml:mo>∑</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mi>i</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>n</mml:mi><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:munderover><mml:mfrac><mml:msub><mml:mi>O</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mi>i</mml:mi><mml:mo>+</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msub><mml:msub><mml:mi>O</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:mfrac><mml:mo>,</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mtd></mml:mtr></mml:mtable></mml:mrow></mml:math><graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_Equ1.gif" position="anchor"/></alternatives></disp-formula><italic>n</italic> being the number of time steps included in this average, by default it is set to 5 in estimateR.</p>
            <p id="Par64">Then, we build the padding values <inline-formula id="IEq128"><alternatives><tex-math id="M235">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$(O_{-y}, \dots , O_{-1})$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M236"><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>O</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mi>y</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mo>⋯</mml:mo><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>O</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq128.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> by<disp-formula id="Equ2"><label>2</label><alternatives><tex-math id="M237">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} O_{-i}&amp;= O_0 \times a^{-i}. \end{aligned}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M238" display="block"><mml:mrow><mml:mtable><mml:mtr><mml:mtd columnalign="right"><mml:msub><mml:mi>O</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:mtd><mml:mtd columnalign="left"><mml:mrow><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>O</mml:mi><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo>×</mml:mo><mml:msup><mml:mi>a</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msup><mml:mo>.</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mtd></mml:mtr></mml:mtable></mml:mrow></mml:math><graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_Equ2.gif" position="anchor"/></alternatives></disp-formula>The number of padding values <italic>y</italic> is proportional to the length of the raw time series <italic>N</italic> and to the smoothing parameter <inline-formula id="IEq129"><alternatives><tex-math id="M239">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\sigma$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M240"><mml:mi>σ</mml:mi></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq129.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>.</p>
            <p id="Par65">After padding, LOESS smoothing is applied, and the smoothed values <inline-formula id="IEq130"><alternatives><tex-math id="M241">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$(S_{-y}, \dots , S_{-1})$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M242"><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>S</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mi>y</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mo>⋯</mml:mo><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>S</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq130.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> are discarded to keep <inline-formula id="IEq131"><alternatives><tex-math id="M243">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$(S_{0}, \dots , S_{N})$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M244"><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>S</mml:mi><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mo>⋯</mml:mo><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>S</mml:mi><mml:mi>N</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq131.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>, the smoothed observations. Finally, the smoothed observations are normalised so that their sum is equal to the total number of raw observations (<inline-formula id="IEq132"><alternatives><tex-math id="M245">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\sum _{i\ge 0} O_i$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M246"><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mo>∑</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mi>i</mml:mi><mml:mo>≥</mml:mo><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msub><mml:msub><mml:mi>O</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq132.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>).</p>
          </sec>
          <sec id="Sec32">
            <title>Estimation of the infection incidence through deconvolution</title>
            <p id="Par66">To recover the non-observed time series of infection incidence from a time series of (optionally-smoothed) observations, estimateR implements a deconvolution algorithm. This algorithm deconvolves the time series of observations with a delay distribution specific to the type of observations (case confirmations, hospital admissions, deaths), to recover an estimate of the time series of infection events. It is an expectation-maximisation algorithm, generalised from the description made by Goldstein et al. [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR19">19</xref>], which is itself an adaptation of the Richardson-Lucy algorithm [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR27">27</xref>, <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR28">28</xref>].</p>
            <p id="Par67">Formally, the method infers a deconvolved output time series <inline-formula id="IEq133"><alternatives><tex-math id="M247">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$(\lambda _{1}, \dots , \lambda _{N})$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M248"><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>λ</mml:mi><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mo>⋯</mml:mo><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>λ</mml:mi><mml:mi>N</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq133.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> from an input time series <inline-formula id="IEq134"><alternatives><tex-math id="M249">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$({\bar{D}}_{K}, \dots , {\bar{D}}_{N})$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M250"><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>D</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">¯</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mover><mml:mi>K</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mo>⋯</mml:mo><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>D</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">¯</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mover><mml:mi>N</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq134.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>, where <inline-formula id="IEq135"><alternatives><tex-math id="M251">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$K \ge \mu$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M252"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>K</mml:mi><mml:mo>≥</mml:mo><mml:mi>μ</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq135.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> (<inline-formula id="IEq136"><alternatives><tex-math id="M253">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mu$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M254"><mml:mi>μ</mml:mi></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq136.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> being the median of the delay distribution) and <inline-formula id="IEq137"><alternatives><tex-math id="M255">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\bar{D}}_{i}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M256"><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>D</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">¯</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mover><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq137.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> indicates the (smoothed) number of observations on time step <italic>i</italic> (e.g., confirmed cases, hospitalisations, or deaths). Let <inline-formula id="IEq138"><alternatives><tex-math id="M257">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$m^{j}_{l}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M258"><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mi>l</mml:mi><mml:mi>j</mml:mi></mml:msubsup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq138.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> be the probability that an infection on time step <italic>j</italic> takes <inline-formula id="IEq139"><alternatives><tex-math id="M259">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$l\ge 0$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M260"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>l</mml:mi><mml:mo>≥</mml:mo><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq139.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> time steps to be observed. If no time-variation of the delay distribution is assumed <inline-formula id="IEq140"><alternatives><tex-math id="M261">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$m^{j}_{l} = m_{l}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M262"><mml:mrow><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mi>l</mml:mi><mml:mi>j</mml:mi></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mi>l</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq140.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>. Let <inline-formula id="IEq141"><alternatives><tex-math id="M263">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$q_{j}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M264"><mml:msub><mml:mi>q</mml:mi><mml:mi>j</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq141.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> be the probability that an infection that occurred on time step <italic>j</italic> is observed during the time-window of observations, i.e. is counted towards <inline-formula id="IEq142"><alternatives><tex-math id="M265">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$({\bar{D}}_{K}, \dots , {\bar{D}}_{N})$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M266"><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>D</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">¯</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mover><mml:mi>K</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mo>⋯</mml:mo><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>D</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">¯</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mover><mml:mi>N</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq142.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>. Then:<disp-formula id="Equ3"><label>3</label><alternatives><tex-math id="M267">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} q_{j}&amp;= \sum _{l = K - j}^{N - j} m^{j}_{l}\,. \end{aligned}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M268" display="block"><mml:mrow><mml:mtable><mml:mtr><mml:mtd columnalign="right"><mml:msub><mml:mi>q</mml:mi><mml:mi>j</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:mtd><mml:mtd columnalign="left"><mml:mrow><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:munderover><mml:mo>∑</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mi>l</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mi>K</mml:mi><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mi>j</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>N</mml:mi><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mi>j</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:munderover><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mi>l</mml:mi><mml:mi>j</mml:mi></mml:msubsup><mml:mspace width="0.166667em"/><mml:mo>.</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mtd></mml:mtr></mml:mtable></mml:mrow></mml:math><graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_Equ3.gif" position="anchor"/></alternatives></disp-formula>Let <inline-formula id="IEq143"><alternatives><tex-math id="M269">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$E_i$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M270"><mml:msub><mml:mi>E</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq143.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> be the expected number of observed cases on time step <italic>i</italic>, for a given infection incidence <inline-formula id="IEq144"><alternatives><tex-math id="M271">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$(\lambda _k)$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M272"><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>λ</mml:mi><mml:mi>k</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq144.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>:<disp-formula id="Equ4"><label>4</label><alternatives><tex-math id="M273">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} E_{i}&amp;= {\left\{ \begin{array}{ll} \sum _{j = 1}^{i} \lambda _{j} \, m_{i-j}^j &amp;{} \text {for} \quad K \ge i \ge N\\ 0 &amp;{} \text {for} \quad 0&lt; i &lt; K\,. \end{array}\right. } \end{aligned}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M274" display="block"><mml:mrow><mml:mtable><mml:mtr><mml:mtd columnalign="right"><mml:msub><mml:mi>E</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:mtd><mml:mtd columnalign="left"><mml:mrow><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mfenced open="{"><mml:mrow><mml:mtable><mml:mtr><mml:mtd columnalign="left"><mml:mrow><mml:msubsup><mml:mo>∑</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mi>j</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msubsup><mml:msub><mml:mi>λ</mml:mi><mml:mi>j</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mspace width="0.166667em"/><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mi>i</mml:mi><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mi>j</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mi>j</mml:mi></mml:msubsup></mml:mrow></mml:mtd><mml:mtd columnalign="left"><mml:mrow><mml:mrow/><mml:mtext>for</mml:mtext><mml:mspace width="1em"/><mml:mi>K</mml:mi><mml:mo>≥</mml:mo><mml:mi>i</mml:mi><mml:mo>≥</mml:mo><mml:mi>N</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:mtd></mml:mtr><mml:mtr><mml:mtd columnalign="left"><mml:mrow><mml:mrow/><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:mtd><mml:mtd columnalign="left"><mml:mrow><mml:mrow/><mml:mtext>for</mml:mtext><mml:mspace width="1em"/><mml:mn>0</mml:mn><mml:mo>&lt;</mml:mo><mml:mi>i</mml:mi><mml:mo>&lt;</mml:mo><mml:mi>K</mml:mi><mml:mspace width="0.166667em"/><mml:mo>.</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mtd></mml:mtr></mml:mtable></mml:mrow></mml:mfenced></mml:mrow></mml:mtd></mml:mtr></mml:mtable></mml:mrow></mml:math><graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_Equ4.gif" position="anchor"/></alternatives></disp-formula>The deconvolution algorithm uses expectation maximisation [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR29">29</xref>] to find a final infection incidence estimate, which has the highest likelihood of explaining the observed input time series. To do so, it starts from an initial guess of the infection incidence time series <inline-formula id="IEq145"><alternatives><tex-math id="M275">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\Lambda ^{0} = (\lambda _{1}^{0}, \dots , \lambda _{N}^{0})$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M276"><mml:mrow><mml:msup><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">Λ</mml:mi><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:msup><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>λ</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mo>⋯</mml:mo><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>λ</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mi>N</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:msubsup><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq145.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>, used to compute <inline-formula id="IEq146"><alternatives><tex-math id="M277">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$E_{i}^{0}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M278"><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>E</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:msubsup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq146.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> according to Eq. <xref rid="Equ4" ref-type="disp-formula">4</xref>, and updates the estimate in each iteration <italic>n</italic> according to the following formula:<disp-formula id="Equ5"><label>5</label><alternatives><tex-math id="M279">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} \lambda ^{n+1}_{j}&amp;= \frac{\lambda ^{n}_{j}}{q_{j}} \cdot \sum _{i = K}^{N} \frac{m_{i-j}^j {\bar{D}}_{i} }{E^{n}_{i}}\,. \end{aligned}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M280" display="block"><mml:mrow><mml:mtable><mml:mtr><mml:mtd columnalign="right"><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>λ</mml:mi><mml:mi>j</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mi>n</mml:mi><mml:mo>+</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup></mml:mtd><mml:mtd columnalign="left"><mml:mrow><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mfrac><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>λ</mml:mi><mml:mi>j</mml:mi><mml:mi>n</mml:mi></mml:msubsup><mml:msub><mml:mi>q</mml:mi><mml:mi>j</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:mfrac><mml:mo>·</mml:mo><mml:munderover><mml:mo>∑</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mi>i</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mi>K</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mi>N</mml:mi></mml:munderover><mml:mfrac><mml:mrow><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mi>i</mml:mi><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mi>j</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mi>j</mml:mi></mml:msubsup><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>D</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">¯</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mover><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:mrow><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>E</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi><mml:mi>n</mml:mi></mml:msubsup></mml:mfrac><mml:mspace width="0.166667em"/><mml:mo>.</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mtd></mml:mtr></mml:mtable></mml:mrow></mml:math><graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_Equ5.gif" position="anchor"/></alternatives></disp-formula>The iteration proceeds until a termination criterion is reached. Here, we follow Goldstein et al. and iterate until the <inline-formula id="IEq147"><alternatives><tex-math id="M281">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\chi ^{2}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M282"><mml:msup><mml:mi>χ</mml:mi><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:msup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq147.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> statistic drops below 1 [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR19">19</xref>]:<disp-formula id="Equ6"><label>6</label><alternatives><tex-math id="M283">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} \chi ^{2}&amp;= \frac{1}{N - K + 1} \sum _{i = K}^{N} \frac{(E^{n}_{i}-{\bar{D}}_{i})^{2}}{E^{n}_{i}}\,, \end{aligned}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M284" display="block"><mml:mrow><mml:mtable><mml:mtr><mml:mtd columnalign="right"><mml:msup><mml:mi>χ</mml:mi><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:msup></mml:mtd><mml:mtd columnalign="left"><mml:mrow><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mfrac><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mrow><mml:mi>N</mml:mi><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mi>K</mml:mi><mml:mo>+</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:mfrac><mml:munderover><mml:mo>∑</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mi>i</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mi>K</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mi>N</mml:mi></mml:munderover><mml:mfrac><mml:msup><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>E</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi><mml:mi>n</mml:mi></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>D</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">¯</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mover><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:msup><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>E</mml:mi><mml:mi>i</mml:mi><mml:mi>n</mml:mi></mml:msubsup></mml:mfrac><mml:mspace width="0.166667em"/><mml:mo>,</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mtd></mml:mtr></mml:mtable></mml:mrow></mml:math><graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_Equ6.gif" position="anchor"/></alternatives></disp-formula>or 100 iterations have been reached.</p>
            <p id="Par68">For the initial estimate of the incidence time series <inline-formula id="IEq148"><alternatives><tex-math id="M285">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\Lambda ^{0}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M286"><mml:msup><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">Λ</mml:mi><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:msup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq148.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>, the time series of observations is shifted backwards in time by the median of the delay distribution <inline-formula id="IEq149"><alternatives><tex-math id="M287">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mu$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M288"><mml:mi>μ</mml:mi></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq149.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>. However, this leaves a gap of unspecified values at the start and end of the time series <inline-formula id="IEq150"><alternatives><tex-math id="M289">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\Lambda _0$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M290"><mml:msub><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">Λ</mml:mi><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq150.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>. We augment the shifted time series with the first observed value (<inline-formula id="IEq151"><alternatives><tex-math id="M291">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\bar{D}}_K$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M292"><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>D</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">¯</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mover><mml:mi>K</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq151.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>) on the left. On the right side, we replace the missing values with an extrapolation of future observations. This extrapolation is specific to estimateR; it is done as follows:<disp-formula id="Equ7"><label>7</label><alternatives><tex-math id="M293">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} \lambda _{N - i}&amp;= {\bar{D}}_N \times \left( \frac{{\bar{D}}_N}{{\bar{D}}_{N - 1}}\right) ^{\mu - i}, \end{aligned}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M294" display="block"><mml:mrow><mml:mtable><mml:mtr><mml:mtd columnalign="right"><mml:msub><mml:mi>λ</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mi>N</mml:mi><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:mtd><mml:mtd columnalign="left"><mml:mrow><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>D</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">¯</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mover><mml:mi>N</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>×</mml:mo><mml:msup><mml:mfenced close=")" open="("><mml:mfrac><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>D</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">¯</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mover><mml:mi>N</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>D</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">¯</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mover><mml:mrow><mml:mi>N</mml:mi><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:mfrac></mml:mfenced><mml:mrow><mml:mi>μ</mml:mi><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msup><mml:mo>,</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mtd></mml:mtr></mml:mtable></mml:mrow></mml:math><graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_Equ7.gif" position="anchor"/></alternatives></disp-formula>for <inline-formula id="IEq152"><alternatives><tex-math id="M295">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$0 \le i &lt; \mu$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M296"><mml:mrow><mml:mn>0</mml:mn><mml:mo>≤</mml:mo><mml:mi>i</mml:mi><mml:mo>&lt;</mml:mo><mml:mi>μ</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq152.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>.</p>
            <p id="Par69"><italic>Time-varying delay distributions</italic> When information on the time variation of delays between symptom onset and observation is available (e.g., through a line list), estimateR can take it into account during the deconvolution step. In this explanation, we need to break down the delay from infection to observation into two successive delays: an incubation period, which we assume to be fixed in time for simplicity, and a delay from onset of symptoms to observation which we allow to vary through time.</p>
            <p id="Par70">Recall that <inline-formula id="IEq153"><alternatives><tex-math id="M297">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$m_{\ell }^j$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M298"><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mi>ℓ</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mi>j</mml:mi></mml:msubsup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq153.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> is the probability that an event occurring at time <italic>j</italic> (corresponding here to the onset of symptoms at time <italic>j</italic>) takes <inline-formula id="IEq154"><alternatives><tex-math id="M299">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\ell$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M300"><mml:mi>ℓ</mml:mi></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq154.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> time steps to be observed. The <inline-formula id="IEq155"><alternatives><tex-math id="M301">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$(m_{0}^j, \dots , m_{\ell _{max}}^j)$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M302"><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mi>j</mml:mi></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mo>⋯</mml:mo><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mi>ℓ</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">max</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:mrow><mml:mi>j</mml:mi></mml:msubsup><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq155.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> time-varying delay distributions from onset of symptoms to observation are determined as follows: for each date <italic>j</italic>, the <inline-formula id="IEq156"><alternatives><tex-math id="M303">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$n_0$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M304"><mml:msub><mml:mi>n</mml:mi><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq156.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> most recent recorded delays between symptom onset and observation, with onset date before <italic>j</italic>, are taken into account; <inline-formula id="IEq157"><alternatives><tex-math id="M305">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\ell _{max}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M306"><mml:msub><mml:mi>ℓ</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="italic">max</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq157.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> being the highest observed delay (over all time steps). In estimateR, <inline-formula id="IEq158"><alternatives><tex-math id="M307">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$n_0$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M308"><mml:msub><mml:mi>n</mml:mi><mml:mn>0</mml:mn></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq158.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> is, by default, at least 500 and up to 20% of all observations (both are flexible parameters).</p>
            <p id="Par71">The incidence data is right-truncated, meaning that, close to the present, hosts with recent onset of symptoms and with longer delay until observation have not been captured yet. Thus, the raw distribution of observed delays is biased towards shorter delays close to the present. To circumvent this effect, we fix the distribution for the reporting delay (<inline-formula id="IEq159"><alternatives><tex-math id="M309">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$m_{\ell }^j$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M310"><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mi>ℓ</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mi>j</mml:mi></mml:msubsup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq159.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>) after a certain time step <italic>j</italic>, so that delay distributions are not downward biased for infection dates close to the present. Let <inline-formula id="IEq160"><alternatives><tex-math id="M311">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
