				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$R_{e}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M358"><mml:msub><mml:mi>R</mml:mi><mml:mi>e</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq181.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> is assumed to be constant on a number of intervals spanning the entire epidemic time window. The boundaries of these intervals must be given as user input.</p>
          </sec>
          <sec id="Sec34">
            <title>Uncertainty estimation</title>
            <p id="Par76">To account for the uncertainty in the raw case observations, a 95% bootstrap confidence intervals is constructed for <inline-formula id="IEq182"><alternatives><tex-math id="M359">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$R_{e}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M360"><mml:msub><mml:mi>R</mml:mi><mml:mi>e</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq182.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>. First, the case observations are re-sampled as follows: given the original case observations <inline-formula id="IEq183"><alternatives><tex-math id="M361">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$D_t, t=K,\dots , N$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M362"><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mi>D</mml:mi><mml:mi>t</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mi>t</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mi>K</mml:mi><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mo>⋯</mml:mo><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mi>N</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq183.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>, LOESS smoothing is applied to the log-transformed data <inline-formula id="IEq184"><alternatives><tex-math id="M363">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$log(D_t+1)$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M364"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>l</mml:mi><mml:mi>o</mml:mi><mml:mi>g</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>D</mml:mi><mml:mi>t</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>+</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq184.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> to obtain the smoothed values <inline-formula id="IEq185"><alternatives><tex-math id="M365">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\hat{h}}_t$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M366"><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>h</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">^</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mi>t</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq185.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> and additive residuals <inline-formula id="IEq186"><alternatives><tex-math id="M367">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$e_t$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M368"><mml:msub><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:mi>t</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq186.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>. Here log-transformation is used to stabilise the variance of the residuals.</p>
            <p id="Par77">From <inline-formula id="IEq187"><alternatives><tex-math id="M369">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$e_t$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M370"><mml:msub><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:mi>t</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq187.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>, residuals are re-sampled to get <inline-formula id="IEq188"><alternatives><tex-math id="M371">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$e^*_t$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M372"><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:mi>t</mml:mi><mml:mo>∗</mml:mo></mml:msubsup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq188.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>. This is done by an overlapping block bootstrap method to account for the time series nature of the data. Specifically, given the original residuals <inline-formula id="IEq189"><alternatives><tex-math id="M373">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$(e_K, \dots , e_N)$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M374"><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:mi>K</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mo>⋯</mml:mo><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:mi>N</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq189.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>, we first sample a block <inline-formula id="IEq190"><alternatives><tex-math id="M375">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$(e^{*1}_1, \dots , e^{*1}_b)$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M376"><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mrow><mml:mrow/><mml:mo>∗</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mo>⋯</mml:mo><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:mi>b</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mrow/><mml:mo>∗</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq190.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> with default block length <inline-formula id="IEq191"><alternatives><tex-math id="M377">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$b=10$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M378"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>b</mml:mi><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>10</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq191.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>. Weekly patterns in case observations can optionally be accounted for, if relevant. If so, the sampled block is built to start on the same day of the week (e.g., Tuesday) as the original case observations <inline-formula id="IEq192"><alternatives><tex-math id="M379">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$D_K$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M380"><mml:msub><mml:mi>D</mml:mi><mml:mi>K</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq192.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>. That is, we keep the longest part <inline-formula id="IEq193"><alternatives><tex-math id="M381">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$(e^{*1}_{m_1}, \dots , e^{*1}_b)$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M382"><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:msub><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mrow/><mml:mo>∗</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mo>⋯</mml:mo><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:mi>b</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mrow/><mml:mo>∗</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq193.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> from <inline-formula id="IEq194"><alternatives><tex-math id="M383">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$(e^{*1}_1, \dots , e^{*1}_b)$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M384"><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mrow><mml:mrow/><mml:mo>∗</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mo>⋯</mml:mo><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:mi>b</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mrow/><mml:mo>∗</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq194.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> such that <inline-formula id="IEq195"><alternatives><tex-math id="M385">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$e^{*1}_{m_1}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M386"><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:msub><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mrow/><mml:mo>∗</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq195.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> has the same day of the week as <inline-formula id="IEq196"><alternatives><tex-math id="M387">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$D_K$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M388"><mml:msub><mml:mi>D</mml:mi><mml:mi>K</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq196.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>. Then, we sample a new block <inline-formula id="IEq197"><alternatives><tex-math id="M389">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$(e^{*2}_1, \dots , e^{*2}_b)$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M390"><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mrow><mml:mrow/><mml:mo>∗</mml:mo><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mo>⋯</mml:mo><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:mi>b</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mrow/><mml:mo>∗</mml:mo><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq197.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> and keep the longest part <inline-formula id="IEq198"><alternatives><tex-math id="M391">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$(e^{*2}_{m_2}, \dots , e^{*2}_b)$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M392"><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:msub><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mrow/><mml:mo>∗</mml:mo><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mo>⋯</mml:mo><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:mi>b</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mrow/><mml:mo>∗</mml:mo><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq198.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> of <inline-formula id="IEq199"><alternatives><tex-math id="M393">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$(e^{*2}_1, \dots , e^{*2}_b)$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M394"><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mrow><mml:mrow/><mml:mo>∗</mml:mo><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mo>⋯</mml:mo><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:mi>b</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mrow/><mml:mo>∗</mml:mo><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq199.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> such that the corresponding day of <inline-formula id="IEq200"><alternatives><tex-math id="M395">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$e^{*2}_{m_2}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M396"><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:msub><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mrow/><mml:mo>∗</mml:mo><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq200.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> follows on <inline-formula id="IEq201"><alternatives><tex-math id="M397">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$e^{*1}_b$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M398"><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:mi>b</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mrow/><mml:mo>∗</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq201.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> (i.e. has the next day of the week if weekly patterns are accounted for). We glue these two sampled blocks together to get the temporal re-sampled residuals <inline-formula id="IEq202"><alternatives><tex-math id="M399">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$(e^{*1}_{m_1}, \dots , e^{*1}_b, e^{*2}_{m_2}, \dots , e^{*2}_b)$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M400"><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:msub><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mrow/><mml:mo>∗</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mo>⋯</mml:mo><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:mi>b</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mrow/><mml:mo>∗</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:msub><mml:mi>m</mml:mi><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mrow/><mml:mo>∗</mml:mo><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mo>⋯</mml:mo><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:mi>b</mml:mi><mml:mrow><mml:mrow/><mml:mo>∗</mml:mo><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq202.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>. We repeat this process of adding blocks until the length of the re-sampled residuals is equal to or larger than the original residuals. In the latter case, we cut the last part of the re-sampled residuals to make sure its length is the same as the original residuals.</p>
            <p id="Par78">Finally, the bootstrap case observations are obtained by<disp-formula id="Equ10"><label>10</label><alternatives><tex-math id="M401">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} D_t^* = \max (\exp ({\hat{h}}_t + e^*_t) -1, 0). \end{aligned}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M402" display="block"><mml:mrow><mml:mtable><mml:mtr><mml:mtd columnalign="right"><mml:mrow><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>D</mml:mi><mml:mi>t</mml:mi><mml:mo>∗</mml:mo></mml:msubsup><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mo movablelimits="true">max</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mo>exp</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mover accent="true"><mml:mi>h</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">^</mml:mo></mml:mover><mml:mi>t</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>+</mml:mo><mml:msubsup><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:mi>t</mml:mi><mml:mo>∗</mml:mo></mml:msubsup><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mn>1</mml:mn><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mn>0</mml:mn><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow><mml:mo>.</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mtd></mml:mtr></mml:mtable></mml:mrow></mml:math><graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_Equ10.gif" position="anchor"/></alternatives></disp-formula>The smoothing-deconvolution-estimation method is applied to the bootstrap case observation to obtain an estimate for <inline-formula id="IEq203"><alternatives><tex-math id="M403">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
