				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$(ar_1 = 0.05, ar_2 = 0.05, ar_3 = -0.02, ar_4 = -0.02)$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M462"><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>a</mml:mi><mml:msub><mml:mi>r</mml:mi><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>0.05</mml:mn><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mi>a</mml:mi><mml:msub><mml:mi>r</mml:mi><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mn>0.05</mml:mn><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mi>a</mml:mi><mml:msub><mml:mi>r</mml:mi><mml:mn>3</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mn>0.02</mml:mn><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mi>a</mml:mi><mml:msub><mml:mi>r</mml:mi><mml:mn>4</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mn>0.02</mml:mn><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq231.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> and standard deviation 0.05. Coefficients are selected to loosely approximate country-level empirical COVID-19 incidence data. The number of observations made on time step <italic>t</italic>, with noise, <inline-formula id="IEq232"><alternatives><tex-math id="M463">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$O_{t}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M464"><mml:msub><mml:mi>O</mml:mi><mml:mi>t</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq232.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> is computed from the generated observations <inline-formula id="IEq233"><alternatives><tex-math id="M465">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$D_t$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M466"><mml:msub><mml:mi>D</mml:mi><mml:mi>t</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq233.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> with:<disp-formula id="Equ12"><label>12</label><alternatives><tex-math id="M467">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} O_{t}&amp;= D_{t} \times e^{\nu _t}. \end{aligned}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M468" display="block"><mml:mrow><mml:mtable><mml:mtr><mml:mtd columnalign="right"><mml:msub><mml:mi>O</mml:mi><mml:mi>t</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:mtd><mml:mtd columnalign="left"><mml:mrow><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>D</mml:mi><mml:mi>t</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo>×</mml:mo><mml:msup><mml:mi>e</mml:mi><mml:msub><mml:mi>ν</mml:mi><mml:mi>t</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:msup><mml:mo>.</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:mtd></mml:mtr></mml:mtable></mml:mrow></mml:math><graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_Equ12.gif" position="anchor"/></alternatives></disp-formula>When comparing estimateR to similar existing methods, we use a different type of noise, as we did not manage to obtain meaningful estimates with epidemia and EpiNow2 with the autocorrelated noise. In this case, the noise factor for each time step <italic>t</italic> (<inline-formula id="IEq234"><alternatives><tex-math id="M469">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\nu _t$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M470"><mml:msub><mml:mi>ν</mml:mi><mml:mi>t</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq234.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>) is an independent random draw from a normal distribution with mean 0 and standard deviation 0.1.</p>
          </sec>
        </sec>
        <sec id="Sec40">
          <title>Appendix D: default settings</title>
          <p id="Par95">In estimateR, by default, the most recent <inline-formula id="IEq235"><alternatives><tex-math id="M471">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$R_e$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M472"><mml:msub><mml:mi>R</mml:mi><mml:mi>e</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq235.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> estimate produced corresponds to the time step <inline-formula id="IEq236"><alternatives><tex-math id="M473">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$N-\mu$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M474"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>N</mml:mi><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mi>μ</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq236.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>, with <italic>N</italic> being the most recent available time step and <inline-formula id="IEq237"><alternatives><tex-math id="M475">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mu$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M476"><mml:mi>μ</mml:mi></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq237.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> being the median of the delay distribution. This truncation is done as posterior <inline-formula id="IEq238"><alternatives><tex-math id="M477">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$R_e$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M478"><mml:msub><mml:mi>R</mml:mi><mml:mi>e</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq238.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> estimates are too uncertain. When dealing with a combination of partially and fully delayed data, the default setting is slightly more complex. In this case, the most recent <inline-formula id="IEq239"><alternatives><tex-math id="M479">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$R_e$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M480"><mml:msub><mml:mi>R</mml:mi><mml:mi>e</mml:mi></mml:msub></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq239.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> estimate corresponds to the time step <inline-formula id="IEq240"><alternatives><tex-math id="M481">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$(N-Y) - \mu$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M482"><mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mi>N</mml:mi><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mi>Y</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo><mml:mo>-</mml:mo><mml:mi>μ</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq240.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> with <italic>Y</italic> being the 33rd percentile of the delay distribution between partially-delayed and fully-delayed observation, <italic>N</italic> and <inline-formula id="IEq241"><alternatives><tex-math id="M483">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mu$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M484"><mml:mi>μ</mml:mi></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="12859_2023_5428_Article_IEq241.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> carry the same meaning as previously. In other words, we first exclude the <italic>Y</italic> most recent time steps for which a partially-delayed observation has a probability less than 0.33 to be fully observed before the most recent time step. The default threshold of 0.33 was chosen as a trade-off between certainty in the result and timeliness of the most recent <inline-formula id="IEq242"><alternatives><tex-math id="M485">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
